{:pack/id "foundations"
 :pack/name "Foundations Pack"
 :pack/version "2026.01.22"
 :pack/description "Core architectural principles: Stratified Design and Simple Made Easy"
 :pack/author "miniforge-official"
 :pack/license "Apache-2.0"

 :pack/categories
 [{:category/id "001"
   :category/name "Stratified Design"
   :category/rules [:001-no-upward-imports
                    :001-no-cycles
                    :001-pure-domain]}
  {:category/id "002"
   :category/name "Simple Made Easy"
   :category/rules [:002-values-over-state
                    :002-data-over-syntax]}]

 :pack/rules
 [;;============================================================================
  ;; Category 001: Stratified Design
  ;;============================================================================

  {:rule/id :001-no-upward-imports
   :rule/title "No upward imports in stratified design"
   :rule/description "Modules may only import from same stratum or below. Never import 'up' the stack."
   :rule/severity :major
   :rule/category "001"

   :rule/applies-to
   {:file-globs ["**/*.clj" "**/*.cljc" "**/*.ts" "**/*.py"]}

   :rule/detection
   {:type :custom
    :custom-fn 'miniforge.packs.foundations/detect-upward-import}

   :rule/agent-behavior
   "Before writing code for a feature, output:
    - A short stratified plan (modules, their stratum, and allowed dependencies)
    - The ports/interfaces to be introduced or reused

    When editing existing code:
    - Detect and call out any 'upward' import or cross-strata leakage
    - If violation found, propose minimal refactor (move interface down, split module, add adapter)

    Canonical strata (innermost to outermost):
    0. Foundations - pure utilities, types, data schemas, constants (no I/O)
    1. Domain - business rules, pure functions, policies, invariants (no I/O)
    2. Application/Use-Cases - orchestration, ports (no infra details)
    3. Adapters - HTTP controllers, CLIs, event handlers, API/DTO mapping
    4. Infrastructure - DB/ORM, queues, caches, cloud SDKs, external services

    Allowed imports: Adapters -> Application -> Domain -> Foundations
    Infrastructure -> (Application|Domain|Foundations) via ports/interfaces only"

   :rule/enforcement
   {:action :hard-halt
    :message "Upward import detected: %s imports from %s (stratum %d -> %d)"
    :remediation "Move the interface to a lower stratum, or inject via port/adapter pattern"}}

  {:rule/id :001-no-cycles
   :rule/title "No import cycles"
   :rule/description "Reject any change that introduces an import/namespace cycle"
   :rule/severity :critical
   :rule/category "001"

   :rule/applies-to
   {:file-globs ["**/*.clj" "**/*.cljc" "**/*.ts" "**/*.py"]}

   :rule/detection
   {:type :custom
    :custom-fn 'miniforge.packs.foundations/detect-import-cycle}

   :rule/agent-behavior
   "Use a single-direction DAG for code dependencies. No cycles. Modules only depend 'down' the stack.

    When a cycle is detected:
    1. Identify which module(s) are causing the cycle
    2. Propose minimal refactor: move interface 'down', split module, or add adapter
    3. Extract shared interfaces to a lower stratum that both modules can depend on

    In PRs, include a tiny import graph (or summary) showing no upward edges/no cycles."

   :rule/enforcement
   {:action :hard-halt
    :message "Import cycle detected: %s"
    :remediation "Break the cycle by extracting shared interface to lower stratum"}}

  {:rule/id :001-pure-domain
   :rule/title "Domain layer must be pure"
   :rule/description "Domain modules must be free of I/O, frameworks, and runtime state"
   :rule/severity :major
   :rule/category "001"

   :rule/applies-to
   {:file-globs ["**/domain/**/*.clj" "**/domain/**/*.cljc"
                 "**/domain/**/*.ts" "**/domain/**/*.py"]}

   :rule/detection
   {:type :content-scan
    :patterns [;; Clojure I/O
               "slurp\\s*\\("
               "spit\\s*\\("
               "clojure\\.java\\.io"
               "http/get"
               "http/post"
               "jdbc/"
               ;; TypeScript I/O
               "fetch\\s*\\("
               "\\bfs\\."
               "axios\\."
               "prisma\\."
               ;; Python I/O
               "\\bopen\\s*\\("
               "requests\\."
               "urllib"
               "sqlalchemy"]}

   :rule/agent-behavior
   "Domain layer must contain only:
    - Pure functions (no side effects)
    - Business rules and invariants
    - Data transformations

    If I/O is needed, define a port (interface) in Application layer and inject adapter.

    Anti-patterns to reject:
    - Domain importing framework/ORM/cloud SDKs
    - Direct file/network operations in domain code
    - Mutable state in domain modules

    Pure core principle: Inject effects at edges. Domain remains referentially transparent."

   :rule/enforcement
   {:action :hard-halt
    :message "I/O detected in Domain layer: %s"
    :remediation "Move I/O to Infrastructure adapter, inject via port"}}

  ;;============================================================================
  ;; Category 002: Simple Made Easy
  ;;============================================================================

  {:rule/id :002-values-over-state
   :rule/title "Prefer values over mutable state"
   :rule/description "Minimize mutable state; make it explicit, local, and small when necessary"
   :rule/severity :minor
   :rule/category "002"

   :rule/applies-to
   {:file-globs ["**/*.clj" "**/*.cljc"]}

   :rule/detection
   {:type :content-scan
    :patterns ["def\\s+\\S+\\s+\\(atom"
               "def\\s+\\S+\\s+\\(ref\\s"
               "volatile!"
               "set!"]}

   :rule/agent-behavior
   "When proposing a design, include:
    1) A short 'simple vs easy' comparison (2-3 bullets)
    2) The minimal set of pure functions and data structures
    3) Where any state is confined and why it's necessary

    Treat state as hazardous material:
    - Justify it, minimize scope, isolate at the edge
    - Model with managed references/STM/actors only when true concurrency requires it

    Prefer idempotent, deterministic operations; make time and randomness injectable.

    Simple = one braid (uncomplected). Easy = familiar/near. Choose simple."

   :rule/enforcement
   {:action :warn
    :message "Mutable state detected: %s. Is this necessary?"
    :remediation "Consider if immutable value + pure function would suffice"}}

  {:rule/id :002-data-over-syntax
   :rule/title "Prefer data over syntax"
   :rule/description "Represent information as plain data (maps, vectors, sets). Avoid DSL-ish micro-syntaxes."
   :rule/severity :minor
   :rule/category "002"

   :rule/applies-to
   {:file-globs ["**/*.clj" "**/*.cljc"]}

   :rule/detection
   {:type :content-scan
    :patterns [;; Macro-heavy patterns that could be data
               "defmacro\\s+def-"
               "defmacro\\s+with-"]}

   :rule/agent-behavior
   "When choosing designs/constructs, prefer options that reduce intertwining of concerns.

    Decision rubric:
    - Values over state: prefer immutable values and pure functions
    - Data over syntax: represent information as plain data (maps, vectors, sets)
    - Functions over methods: favor small, stateless functions over deep OO hierarchies
    - Declarative over imperative: use set/relational operations for 'what', not 'how'

    When editing code that's overly complex:
    - Suggest a 'data first' rewrite of the hot path
    - Extract policy into a dedicated rules module or data file
    - Replace switch/if jungles with open polymorphism where beneficial

    Accept that simple != fewer things. More but smaller modules is often better."

   :rule/enforcement
   {:action :warn
    :message "Consider if macro could be replaced with data: %s"
    :remediation "Represent configuration/rules as EDN data rather than macro DSL"}}]}
